PEER GROUP MASTERMINDS 
When I first started my own business, I was taken along by my business partner to a non-paid peer group Mastermind in Birmingham, with 8 successful entrepreneurs.

I was so far out of my depth it was embarrassing. 
I sat and listened to the questions being presented and avoided saying what I thought in case it was wrong.

We had meet ups every 6 months and at every meet I gained more confident, and more knowledgeable. 
A few weeks ago I met one of the members at a different event. And they asked for my advice on a challenge he is having. 
Without hesitation I gave him my help, and guided him to a decision. 
It was only this week when they thanked me for the help that I realised how much I had learned by listening to experienced entrepreneurs like them, in a mastermind environment.

In hindsight, It was one of the most uncomfortable but ultimately rewarding thing I have ever done.

Get yourself in a room where you are the least experienced, earning the least and least knowledgeable üí™üèªüí•üî• #mastermind #entrepreneur #learning #youngentrepreneurs #startupuk

Last summer, I travelled to the US with my wife with the sole purpose of seeing a band. It sounds ridiculous every time I say it... Oklahoma and Denver, in a week, without our 2 kids...‚úàÔ∏è On the flight home, I started to think about how I could creat superfans. 1. Serving at the highest level - ever heard the phrase givers gain? Share your knowledge and expertise with people that need it. Answer questions openly and honestly without thinking about ¬£¬£¬£ 2. Acknowledgement - when they comment on your posts, comment back. When they DM you, DM them back. Publicly thank them for supporting you.
